              <span id="reviewTextContainer4090016359" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15657208354513244150">I picked this up in a street library, started reading it while I walked and finished it off with coffee sitting in the big black chair. I thought it would be mildly amusing, but it is much better than that.<br/> <br/>Old now, published a quarter of a century ago, the critique is still most relevant. Garnerâ€™s strength is his thoroughness, he transforms every â€˜unacceptableâ€™ element into politically correct terms. He also applies contemporary touches when relevant and amusing: the prince who was turned into </span>
  <span id="freeText15657208354513244150" style="display:none">I picked this up in a street library, started reading it while I walked and finished it off with coffee sitting in the big black chair. I thought it would be mildly amusing, but it is much better than that.<br /> <br />Old now, published a quarter of a century ago, the critique is still most relevant. Garnerâ€™s strength is his thoroughness, he transforms every â€˜unacceptableâ€™ element into politically correct terms. He also applies contemporary touches when relevant and amusing: the prince who was turned into a frog in this case is a real estate developer, so when the disgusted princess throws him back in the pond, noâ€“one misses him. Boom! Boom! <br /><br />Fairy tales (now an unacceptable term), are a rich field for this sort of treatment for they are full of ageism, sexism, speciesism, racism, oppression and intolerance, among other bad things. There are neat twists: when the clock strikes midnight Cinderellaâ€™s fine but restrictive clothes and impractical glass slippers are instantly replaced by comfortable rags and bare feet, leading the dolled up â€˜womynâ€™ present to do likewise and throw off their oppressive finery.<br /><br />All the stories are fun, but a few are inspired. I particularly like <i>Snow White</i>. It boasts the renamed â€˜Seven Towering Giantsâ€™, a prince with a personal problem which is directly addressed when he catches sight of the winsome sleeping princess, and it has my favourite line in the whole book. The leader of the Seven Towering Giants reveals to Snow White that they no longer dig in the mines as the rape of the planet is immoral: <blockquote>'So now we are dedicated stewards of the earth and live here in harmony with nature. To make ends meet, we also conduct retreats for men who need to get in touch with their primitive masculine identities.â€™<br /><br />â€˜So what does that involve,â€™ asked Snow White, â€˜Aside from drinking milk straight from the carton?â€™</blockquote>PS: There are lots of good reviews of this title.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15657208354513244150" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


